nia -- t15. Environmental Impact Assessment in the Russian Federation -- t16. Environmental Impact Assessment in Serbia -- t17. Environmental Impact Assessment in the Slovak Republic -- t18. Environmental Impact Assessment in Slovenia -- t19. Environmental Impact Assessment in Ukraine: History and Recent Developments -- t20. Comparison and Evaluation of EIA Systems in Countries in Transition -- tPart III SOME LEADING ISSUES: WORKSHOP GROUP FINDINGS -- tWorkshop Group Findings -- tWorkshop 1: Responsibility / Authority For Carrying Out EIAs -- tWorkshop 2: Enforcement of EIA Legislation and Regulations -- tWorkshop 3: Quality Control of the EIA Process -- tWorkshop 4: Effectiveness of EIA As a Tool of Environmental Planning and Environmental Management -- tWorkshop 5: Integrating EIA into Planning and Decision Making -- tWorkshop 6: Integration of Cost Benefit Analysis and EIA -- tWorkshop 7: How to Integrate Social, Health and Risk Assessment into EIA -- tWorkshop 8: Linkages between EIA and Other Environmental Legislation -- tWorkshop 9: Consultation and Public Participation -- tWorkshop 10: Determining The Significance of Impacts -- tWorkshop 11: Strategic Environmental Assessment -- tWorkshop 12: Training for EIA and SEA -- tPart IV CONCLUSIONS AND RECOMMENDATIONS -- tConclusions and Recommendations -- tAppendix. Use of Models in EIA0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe countries included in this study on the regulations and practices relating environmental assessment are Armenia, Belarus, Bulgaria, Croatia, the Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Kazakhstan, Latvia, Lithuania, Moldova, Montenegro, Poland, Romania, Russia, Slovenia, Ukraine. Each country study has been prepared by specialists from within the country concerned. This study will be of interest to EA practitioners in public administration; development and consultant organizations; training and educational and research institutes; and international and bilateral aid agencies. Project level EIA (Environmental Impact Assessment) and, to a lesser extent, SEA (Strategic Environmental Assessment) for planning and other strategic-level actions have been, or are being, introduced in the great majority of countries in transition (CIT). As yet, however, most of the countries have only limited experience in formulating "state of the art" EIA regulations and applying them satisfactorily. Furthermore, such experiences in CITs that do exist are not yet sufficiently well documented and widely disseminated. This report should be of considerable value in helping strengthen EA regulation and practice in the region.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aEnvironmental impact analysisxLaw and legislationzEurope, Eastern. 0aEnvironmental impact analysisxLaw and legislationzFormer Soviet republics. 0aEnvironmental impact analysiszEurope, Eastern. 0aEnvironmental impact analysiszFormer Soviet republics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.2bisacsh  aeffectiveness, Central and Eastern Europe,.  aoperation.1 aAnachkova, Svetla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBellinger, Edward G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBuciunaite, Irena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurja, Alenka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCherp, Oleg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDermelj, Marjana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeorge, Clive, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeorge, Clive, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGruin, Mirela, econtributor.4ctb4https://i